      <hedline>
        <hl1>What's on a Candidate's Bookshelf?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Sarah Hopkins letter on Michael Beschloss's June 11 Op-Ed article on presidential reading habits; says that what concerns electorate is not George W Bush's book list but his derision of intellectuals and disdain for learning (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''How Well Read Should a President Be?'' (Op-Ed, June 11):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''How Well Read Should a President Be?'' (Op-Ed, June 11):</p>
        <p>It is not George W. Bush's reading list that concerns the electorate but his anti-intellectual stance. Equipped with degrees from some of the best schools, Mr. Bush, while deriding intellectuals, says he would be an ''education president.'' I have little interest for what Mr. Bush has on his bookshelf, but I would mind an ''education president'' who disdains learning.</p>
        <p>SARAH HOPKINS  New York, June 12, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
